{{Infobox holiday |holiday_name = Dozhynki |type = ethnic |image = Последний-сноп.jpg |imagesize = |caption =<small>Last sheaf. Russia. Photos of the early 20th century</small> |official_name = |nickname = {{lang-ru|Обжинки|Obzhynki}}; {{lang-be|Прачыстая}}, ''[[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Prachystaya]]''; {{lang-cs|Dožínky}}; {{lang-csb|Òżniwinë}}; ''[[Dormition of the Theotokos|Dormition]]'' |observedby = [[Slavic people]] |litcolor = |longtype = |significance = The end of the harvest crops |begins = |ends = |date =August 15 (28). In some regions of Russia Dozhinki rites performed September 8 (21) or September 14 (27). <!-- Use next three if holiday is the same day of the same week every year --> |week_ordinal = <!-- "first", "second", "last", etc. --> |weekday = <!-- "Sunday", "Monday", "Friday", etc. --> |month = <!-- "January", "February", "December", etc. --> <!-- Use next three if the date changes in an unusual pattern each year --> |date2012 = <!-- only for days that change each year --> |date2013 = <!-- only for days that change each year --> |date2014 = <!-- only for days that change each year --> |celebrations = |observances = |relatedto = }} [[File:Side road effigy during Dożynki festival near Wroclaw.jpg|thumb|Side road effigy during Dożynki festival near Wroclaw]] '''Dożynki''' (''Dozhinki'', {{lang-ua|Обжинки|Obzhynky}}, {{lang-pl|Dożynki}}, {{lang-ru|Обжинки|Obzhynki}}; {{lang-be|Прачыстая}}, ''[[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Prachystaya]]''; {{lang-cs|Dožínky, Obžinky}}; {{lang-csb|Òżniwinë}}; ''[[Dormition of the Theotokos|Dormition]]'') is a [[Slavic peoples|Slavic]] [[harvest festival]]. In pre-Christian times the feast usually fell on the [[Equinox|autumn equinox]]{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}, in modern times it is usually celebrated on one of the Sundays following the end of the [[Harvest|harvest season]], which fall on different days in different regions of Europe.
The feast was initially associated with the [[Slavic mythology|pagan Slavic]] cult of plants, trees and agriculture.{{sfn|Ogrodowska|2004|loc=s.v. Dożynki}} In [[16th century]] in Central and Eastern Europe it gained a Christian character and started to be organised by the [[Szlachta|landed gentry]] and more affluent [[peasant]]s as a means to thank the reapers and their families for their work, both during the harvest and during the past year.{{sfn|Ogrodowska|2004|loc=s.v. Dożynki}}{{sfn|Biernacka|Kopczyńska-Jaworska|Kutrzeba-Pojnarowa|Paprocka|1981|p=147}}
While there are many regional varieties and traditions, most have some aspects in common. Often the peasants or farmers celebrating ''dożynki'' gather in the fields outside their village, form a [[procession]] and bring back a [[Sheaf (agriculture)|sheaf]] or the last batch of cereal reaped from nearby fields.{{sfn|Biernacka|Kopczyńska-Jaworska|Kutrzeba-Pojnarowa|Paprocka|1981|p=147}} The women would then turn it into a wreath and offer it to the guest of honour (usually the organiser of the celebration: a local noble, the richest farmer in the village or – in modern times – the [[vogt]] or other representative of the authorities).
== Names == In Poland, where the tradition survived to modern times, the feast and accompanying rituals are known under a variety of names depending on the region. The prevalent term is ''dożynki'', but ''wyżynki'', ''obrzynki'', ''wieniec'', ''wieńcowe'', ''żniwniok'' or ''okrężne'' are also used in some areas.{{sfn|Kuchowicz|1975|p=409}}
Similarly, in Belarus there are a variety of names in use, including the Feast of the [[Theotokos|Most Clean One]] ({{Lang-be|Першая Прачыстая}}), Aspazha ({{Lang-be|Аспажа|links = no}}), Haspazha ({{Lang-be|Гаспажа|links = no}}), Great Spazha ({{Lang-be|Вялікая Спажа|links = no}}), Zelnya ({{Lang-be|Зельная|links = no}}), Talaka ({{Lang-be|Талака|links = no}}) and Dazhynki ({{Lang-be|Дажынкі|links = no}}).{{sfn|Усачёва|2004|pp=448–452}} In Belarusian culture it is often associated and intermixed with the feasts of the [[Assumption of Mary]] (often dubbed the feast of the Mother of God of the Herbs in both Polish and Belarusian), hence the names of Green Feast ({{Lang-be|Зялёная|links = no}}) and [[Dormition of the Mother of God|Dormition]] ({{Lang-be|Успленье|links = no}}) are also used.{{sfn|Усачёва|2004|pp=448–452}}
== History ==
As with many other Slavic feasts and rites, the origins of Slavic harvest festivals are unclear, in large part due to lack of historical documents from pre-Christian times. It is certain however, that both [[Western Slavs|Western]] and [[Eastern Slavs]] formed mostly agricultural cultures and worshipped deities associated with working the land and passage of seasons.{{sfn|Niewiadomski|1991|p=86}} For instance every year at the end of the harvest the West Slavic tribe of [[Rani (Slavic tribe)|Rani]] would gather around the temple in [[Jaromarsburg|Arkona]].{{sfn|Niewiadomski|1991|p=86}} Among the offerings to the god [[Svetovid]] was a large, human-sized pancake made of newly threshed grain from that years' harvest.{{sfn|Niewiadomski|1991|p=86}} If the pancake was large enough for the priest to hide behind it, the Slavs believed next year's harvest would be equally rich.{{sfn|Niewiadomski|1991|p=86}} Apparently a wreath made of the last straws left on the field at the end of the harvest was also believed to possess magical powers.{{sfn|Seweryn|1932|p=35}}
== Common features == [[File:Wierusz-Kowalski Dożynki 1910.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Alfred Wierusz-Kowalski]]. Dożynki. Poland, 1910]] The wreath is a central feature of most celebrations associated with ''dożynki'', as it symbolises a rich harvest, the prospect of wealth and the power of new life vested in the grain gathered during the Summer.{{sfn|Niewiadomski|1991|p=85}} The latter probably explains why in many regions the grain from the wreath is used as the first batch of grain threshed and set aside for next year's sowing (for instance this practice is common in the [[Holy Cross Mountains]] of Central Poland).{{sfn|Niewiadomski|1991|p=86}}
Originally the wreath was in fact a decorated sheaf of grain, decorated with field flowers, ribbons and braided straws.{{sfn|Seweryn|1932|pp=35–36}} In fact such wreaths were still being made in Poland in the 1930s.{{sfn|Seweryn|1932|pp=35–36}} However, with time other forms of wreath became more popular, including the now-typical round wreath, but crown-shaped, oval or rectangular wreaths are also popular in various regions.{{sfn|Seweryn|1932|pp=35–36}}
The sheaf or the wreath is usually brought back into the village by a ceremonial procession. It is often blessed, either by a Christian priest, or in an extra-religious way.{{sfn|Niewiadomski|1991|p=86}} For instance in [[Masovia]] the wreath is usually brought to the church for the Catholic priest to bless it with [[holy water]].{{sfn|Niewiadomski|1991|p=86}} In other regions however it is the priest (Catholic, Orthodox or Greek Catholic) who is brought to the site where the final celebrations take place.{{sfn|Niewiadomski|1991|p=86}} <!-- === Wreath ===
=== Procession ===
-->
=== Time frame === Originally the pre-Christian rite was performed on the autumn equinox{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} (23 September). With time the rite became more closely associated with the actual end of fieldwork in the particular region. However, the time between the end of harvest and the festivities varies from area to area.{{sfn|Niewiadomski|1991|p=87}} For instance, in the vicinity of [[Kielce]] in central Poland and [[Kraków]] in southern Poland the wreath was traditionally blessed already on the Feast of the [[Assumption of Mary]] (15 August); it was then stored for a night or two in the house of the [[Elder (administrative title)|elder]] and the manor, before being threshed and the grain immediately sowed in the fields.{{sfn|Niewiadomski|1991|p=87}}
==In Russia== It is the ethnolinguistic phenomenon in the history the day of the {{Interlanguage link multi|folk calendar of the Eastern Slavs|ru|3=Народный календарь восточных славян|vertical-align=sup}} and the completion of the harvest ritual, falling in many places August 15 (28), in other places celebrated in September. By mid-August harvest grain ends, hence the name of the holiday. Includes the rituals associated with last (dozhinochnym) [[Sheaf (agriculture)|sheaf]], the ritual of "curling beard" and a celebratory meal.
Almost lost in Russia at the Soviet period.{{sfn|Lane|1981|p=124}} In the post-Soviet period this folk tradition in some countries has been recreated as an official holiday.
==In Poland== Harvest Festival in [[Poland]] has been celebrated after the harvest since the time of the feudal systems. In present-day Poland the ''Presidential Harvest Festival'' was created in 1929.
