{{About||Illinois's primary state fair|Illinois State Fair}}
{{Infobox recurring event | name = Du Quoin State Fair | logo = | logo_caption = | image = | caption = | genre = State fair | date = | begins = | ends = | frequency = Annually | venue = | location = | coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | country = | years_active = | first = {{Start date|1923|df=y}} | founder_name = | last = August 24 - September 3, 2018 | prev = | next = TBA | participants = | attendance = | area = | budget = | activity = | patron = | organised = <!--"organized=" also works--> | filing = <!-- Filing status --> | people = | member = | sponsor = | website = | footnotes = }}
The '''DuQuoin State Fair''' is an annual festival, centering on the themes of [[agriculture]] and [[country music]], hosted by the [[U.S. state]] of [[Illinois]] on a 1,200-acre fairground site adjacent to the southern Illinois town of [[Du Quoin, Illinois|Du Quoin]]. The [[state fair]] has been celebrated almost every year since 1923. Currently, the fair is held annually over an 11-day period concluding on [[Labor Day]] of each year. In 2018, the State Fair was held from August 24 through September 3, and an admission fee was charged.<ref name="IDOA">{{cite web |url=https://www.agr.state.il.us/dq/ |title=Growing Illinois: DuQuoin State Fair |work=[[Illinois Department of Agriculture]] |accessdate=2015-08-27 |format=}}</ref>
==History and current events== The DuQuoin Fair was organized in 1923 by William R. "W.R." Hayes and a consortium of Du Quoin developers. They promoted the private-sector enterprise as a short-duration [[Horse racing|race meeting]] specializing in [[harness racing]]. Starting with a half-mile track, the developer eventually built the mile-long [[DuQuoin State Fairgrounds Racetrack]] on the fairgrounds. The racetrack hosted the [[Hambletonian Stakes|Hambletonian]] trotting event in 1957-1980 and the ''World Trotting Derby'' in 1981-2009. The racetrack is used today for [[Automobile Racing Club of America|ARCA]] and [[United States Auto Club|USAC]] motor sporting events.
With the departure of the Hambletonian, the DuQuoin Fair faced economic challenges and was taken over from the private sector in the 1980s by the state of Illinois. Since that time, it has been operated by the [[Illinois Department of Agriculture]] as a state fair with a distinctive [[Southern Illinois]] heritage.<ref name="IDOA"/>
Although the host town of the fair is spelled "Du Quoin", with a space, the Department of Agriculture refers to the fair as the "DuQuoin State Fair", with the space omitted.<ref name="IDOA"/>
